  "prompt": "In outer space how do rockets move if there environment is a vacuum?",
  "response": "Rockets are able to move in outer space, which is a vacuum, through the principle of Newton's Third Law of Motion: For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. \n\nHere's how it works:\n\n1. **Propellant Ejection**: Rockets carry their own fuel and oxidizer. The rocket engine burns this propellant, creating high-speed exhaust gases.\n\n2. **Action and Reaction**: When the rocket engine expels these gases out of the nozzle at high speeds, it generates a force in the opposite direction. This is the action force.\n\n3. **Thrust**: The reaction to this action force pushes the rocket forward. This forward force is known as thrust.\n\nSince a rocket carries all the necessary materials (fuel and oxidizer) to produce thrust, it does not rely on atmospheric pressure or external air, making it fully capable of functioning in the vacuum of space. This system works regardless of whether the rocket is in the atmosphere or in the vacuum of space.",
